Security Operations Fundamentals > [T2]: Automating Security Incident Response with SOAR (Security Orchestration, Automation, and Response)

Security Orchestration, Automation, and Response (SOAR)

Defending organizations is a challenging job. Analyzing and responding to hundreds of alerts is difficult, time-consuming, and exhausting. SOC analysts face many challenges in their day-to-day job, and "Alert Fatigue" is a major one. 

Alert fatigue happens when a security analyst is exposed to an overwhelming number of alerts to the extent that impacts performance and results in burnout. The higher the number of alerts, the higher the likelihood of alert fatigue, resulting in crucial threats going undetected. While alerts are designed to signal a potential problem, they also require some manual investigation to confirm whether they are genuine or not.

According to a study by TrendMicro, which polled 2,303 IT security and SOC decision-makers across companies of all sizes and verticals:

"70% of respondents say their home lives are being emotionally impacted by their work managing IT threat alerts."

Remember that mental health is very IMPORTANT. If you feel stressed, talk to your manager or search for an alternative employer if that does not help. 

That situation generated the need to find an efficient way to handle big chunks of alerts. Fine-tuning log policies and prioritizing which logs to collect helped a lot but could not accommodate the increasing number of events and alerts generated in a typical network. That situation triggered the need for automation! Automation refers to using technology to reduce human intervention as much as possible. Security Orchestration, Automation, and Response (SOAR) refer to the technologies and tools used to help security analysts utilize automation. 

Gartner defines Security Orchestration, Automation, and Response (SOAR) as follows:

"SOAR refers to technologies that enable organizations to collect inputs monitored by the security operations team. For example, alerts from the SIEM system and other security technologies where incident analysis and triage can be performed by leveraging a combination of human and machine power help define, prioritize and drive standardized incident response activities. SOAR tools allow organizations to define incident analysis and response procedures in a digital workflow format."

Figure - zoom in

SOAR provides SOC analysts with the following advantages:

  • Accelerating incident response, thanks to pre-defined playbooks.
  • Reducing false positives.
  • Reducing analyst fatigue by performing repetitive tasks.
  • Fewer mistakes during investigations.
  • More focus on critical incidents and investigations.


Some may confuse SIEM with SOAR. A SOAR can be a SIEM add-on/plugin or a fully-blown standalone platform. You can think of SOAR as an automation add-on to the SIEM.
